"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.1.8.3\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.1.8.3</span> Winnowing fork</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">זרה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(zarah (verb))</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ruth3:2\">RUT 3:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov20:8\">PRO 20:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov20:26\">PRO 20:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:24\">ISA 30:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa41:16\">ISA 41:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer4:11\">JER 4:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer15:7\">JER 15:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer51:2\">JER 51:2</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מִזְרֶה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mizreh)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:24\">ISA 30:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer15:7\">JER 15:7</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">רַחַת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(rachath)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:24\">ISA 30:24</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">λικμάω</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(likmaō (verb))</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir5:9\">SIR 5:9</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">πτύον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(ptuon)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:12\">MAT 3:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:17\">LUK 3:17</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0072_man_holding_goad_with_ox_pulling_threshing_sledge.png\" alt=\"\n            \"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">\n             (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>The winnowing fork was a wooden fork-like implement, with five to seven prongs, for throwing threshed grain into the air so that the wind might separate the straw and chaff from the grain.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>See <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.1.8 Threshing and winnowing&lt;REALIA:1.1.8&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/UBS-0006_winnowing_fork.jpg\" alt=\"A winnowing fork is used in separating grain from chaff\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">A winnowing fork is used in separating grain from chaff (© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart by United Bible Societies)</figcaption></figure>Where there is no receptor-language term for a winnowing fork, translators may choose a descriptive phrase, for example, “a tool for throwing threshed grain into the air in order to let the chaff blow away.”</p>\n<p>The Hebrew verb <em>zarah</em> means literally “to scatter.” It refers to a variety of operations in Scripture, including the process of winnowing.</p>\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0326_winnowing_shovel.jpg\" alt=\"Wooden Spade, possibly used in winnowing (watercolor and graphite on paper, Archie Thompson, 1938)\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Wooden Spade, possibly used in winnowing (watercolor and graphite on paper, Archie Thompson, 1938) (National Gallery of Art, CC0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The Hebrew word <em>rachath</em> appears only once in Scripture at <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:24\">ISA 30:24</a>, where its meaning is uncertain. It probably refers to a wooden implement with a long, flat blade attached to a long handle, similar to a spade but made of wood. The verse names two objects for performing the different stages of winnowing. The point of the verse is that even the food given to the animals will have been thoroughly prepared. Some translations eliminate the need to translate an implement by following the Septuagint; for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> has “Even the oxen and donkeys that plow your fields will be fed the finest grain.”</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir5:9\">SIR 5:9</a> the activity of winnowing is used in a proverb. The literal text of the New Revised Standard Version (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Revised Standard Version (1989)\">NRSV</abbr>) says “Do not winnow in every wind, or follow every path,” but <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> restructures (and reverses the order of) verses 9 and 10 to give the meaning of the proverb: “Don’t try to please everyone or agree with everything people say.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
